SIMPLE: fill
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fill
<hw>Fill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Thill</er>.]</ety> <def>One of the thills or shafts of a
carriage.</def> <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fill horse</b></col>, <cd>a thill horse.</cd>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fill
<hw>Fill</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Filled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Filling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>fillen</ets>,
<ets>fullen</ets>, AS. <ets>fyllan</ets>, fr. <ets>full</ets> full; akin
to D. <ets>vullen</ets>, G. <ets>f⟦uum⟧llen</ets>, Icel.
<ets>fylla</ets>, Sw. <ets>fylla</ets>, Dan. <ets>fylde</ets>, Goth.
<ets>fulljan</ets>. See <er>Full</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To make full; to supply with as much as can be held or contained;
to put or pour into, till no more can be received; to occupy the whole
capacity of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rain also <qex>filleth</qex> the pools.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
lxxxiv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Jesus saith unto them, <qex>Fill</qex> the waterpots with water.
Anf they <qex>filled</qex> them up to the brim.</q> <rj><qau>John ii.
7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish an abudant supply to; to furnish with as
mush as is desired or desirable; to occupy the whole of; to swarm in or
overrun.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And God blessed them, saying. Be fruitful, and multiply, and
<qex>fill</qex> the waters in the seas.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Syrians <qex>filled</qex> the country.</q> <rj><qau>1 Kings
xx. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fill or supply fully with food; to feed; to
satisfy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whence should we have so much bread in the wilderness, as to
<qex>fill</qex>so great a multitude?</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xv.
33.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Things that are sweet and fat are more <qex>filling</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To possess and perform the duties of; to officiate
in, as an incumbent; to occupy; to hold; <as>as, a king <ex>fills</ex> a
throne; the president <ex>fills</ex> the office of chief magistrate; the
speaker of the House <ex>fills</ex> the chair.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To supply with an incumbent; <as>as, to
<ex>fill</ex> an office or a vacancy</as>.</def> <rj><au>A.
Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To press and dilate,
as a sail; <as>as, the wind <ex>filled</ex> the sails</as>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>To trim (a yard) so that the wind shall blow on the
after side of the sails.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Civil Engineering)</fld> <def>To make an embankment
in, or raise the level of (a low place), with earth or gravel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fill in</b></col>, <cd>to insert; as, he <xex>filled
in</xex> the figures.</cd> -- <col><b>To fill out</b></col>, <cd>to
extend or enlarge to the desired limit; to make complete; as, to
<xex>fill out</xex> a bill.</cd> -- <col><b>To fill up</b></col>, <cd>to
make quite full; to fill to the brim or entirely; to occupy completely;
to complete.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The bliss that <xex>fills up</xex> all the
mind.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Pope.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧And <xex>fill up</xex> that which is
behind of the afflictions of Christ.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Col. i.
24.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fill
<hw>Fill</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become
full; to have the whole capacity occupied; to have an abundant supply;
to be satiated; <as>as, corn <ex>fills</ex> well in a warm season; the
sail <ex>fills</ex> with the wind.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill a cup or glass for drinking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give me some wine; <qex>fill</qex> full.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To back and fill</b></col>. See under <er>Back</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos> -- <col><b>To fill up</b></col>, <cd>to grow or become
quite full; as, the channel of the river <xex>fills up</xex> with
sand.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fill</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fill
<hw>Fill</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>fyllo</ets>. See
<er>Fill</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A full supply,
as much as supplies want; as much as gives complete satisfaction.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Ye shall eat your <xex>fill</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Lev. xxv.
19.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll bear thee hence, where I may weep my <qex>fill</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which fills; filling; filler; specif., an
embankment, as in railroad construction, to fill a hollow or ravine;
also, the place which is to be filled.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Filled cheese</ent>⟦br⟧
